AGI -&nbsp; For a few hours, Capri was the navel of world foreign policy. It was from Wednesday evening that between the alleys that climb on the island, in front of the Gulf of Naples, the ranks of international diplomacy were held. Tourists and cameramen, delegations and restaurateurs, all mixed without apparent hindrance. Moreover the island is accustomed to great events: There was Jacqueline Kennedy, in summer you can see Leonardo Di Caprio and Jennifer Lopez, no one gets surprised at anything. At least of the candlelight dinner of the head of the U.S. diplomacy, Antony Blinken>, with his wife, on a terrace overlooking the iconic sitting room. < a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-19/Israel-attack-l-iran-diverse-explosions-droni-culprono-base-military-26081062/"
&nbsp;
He was the Foreign Minister, Antonio Tajani>, who gave the world the announcement that the US had been warned "last minute" of the raid. American sources added that it was an Israeli missile targeting Iran. Blinken clarified that the US had not been involved in any action, but refused to confirm that Israel had given Washington notice of the action: "I am not going to talk about it except to say that the United States has not been involved in any offensive operation."
&nbsp;
It is &nbsp;a time when relations between the United States and their main ally in the Middle East are increasingly icy and from the tone you understand. There have been explosions in Isfahan and Tabriz, perhaps even in Syria, but Iran minimizes >: it lets know that nothing special happened and there will be no retaliation attack. And while from the Middle East there are news, in Capri the slogans are de-escalation and moderation>. The ministers repeat it, sums up the final document signed.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"He prevailed, there were no casualties," Tajani points out when he meets the press after almost three hours of interview with his colleagues. The fear that Israel gave a incendiary response to the attack suffered last Saturday by Iran seems to be now blurred. "When friends send a message, it obviously triggers a reflection," notes the vice premier who promises further commitment to de-escalation. Today is the first step: "I don't know how much it is possible that Israel and Iran sit around a table but now it counts de-escalation, which concludes this phase and opens a different season: coming to a truce, bringing in aid to Gaza, freeing hostages, reducing the aggression of Houthi and Hezbollah."
&nbsp;
Italy, which has the G7 presidency, can play a leading role, incalza Blinken. "Speak with those who have good relations in the Middle East": the obvious reference is to Iran. "Italy has direct contacts and I think it has been seen in the last two weeks. It is important to feed them to avoid escalation and a broader, regional conflict." Minister Tajani, when do you call Iran? Tajani, who is now leaving the island and enjoys the greetings and compliments of the islanders before climbing on the ferry, turns surprised: "Give me a breath, it just ended this day."

